article.description:
Katie Robinette scored 18 points and grabbed a
career-high 14 rebounds and No. 21 Iowa State overcame stretches of
ragged play to beat Texas A&M 68-54 on Saturday.
article.headline: Robinette, Medders post double-doubles for Iowa State
article.linkText: No. 21 Cyclones lapse, still flatten Aggies
article.story:
AMES, Iowa (AP) -- Mary Fox made sure her family didn't ride a
bus 700 miles for nothing.

Fox hit two critical 3-pointers down the stretch and Katie
Robinette had 18 points and a career-high 14 rebounds to help No.
21 Iowa State get past Texas A&M 68-54 on Saturday.

About 35 family members from the Cleveland, Ohio, area saw Fox
go 4-for-9 on 3-pointers and finish with 15 points, six rebounds
and two steals.

"What section was all of Fox's people sitting in?" Texas A&M
coach Gary Blair said. "They had a lot to cheer about because it
seemed she hit every big shot when we made a defensive mistake."

Lyndsey Medders also had a double-double for Iowa State (21-5,
11-4 Big 12), finishing with 14 points and 10 assists, the last one
coming on a pass to Robinette for a layup that topped off the
victory with 20 seconds left.

Anne O'Neil added 15 points and six assists for the Cyclones,
who are the Big 12's highest scoring and best shooting team but
didn't look the part of much of the game. That allowed Texas A&M
(14-12, 4-11) to hang around despite shooting 28.8 percent.

"When you play a team like this that's basically the polar
opposite of our team, sometimes we look good when we do what we
want to do," Iowa State coach Bill Fennelly said. "Sometimes they
look good when they do what they want to do and in the middle, it's
kind of ugly."

The Aggies trailed by only four midway through the second half
and were down just 48-43 after Tamea Scales made two free throws
with 7:23 remaining.

But Medders hit a 3-pointer and Fox sank two 3s over the next 2½
minutes, enabling the Cyclones to finally stretch their lead. Fox's
second 3, with 4:50 remaining, came after A&M had pulled to 55-48
and illustrated Iowa State at its best.

Robinette had rebounded an A&M miss and fired the ball to
Medders, who passed to O'Neil, who found Fox wide open in the left
corner.

"That extra pass is huge," Fox said. "The passer is probably
wide open and that extra pass shows how unselfish our team is. It
put me in the right place."

Medders then sank two free throws and the 6-foot-2 Robinette,
taller than any of her defenders, got a basket inside to make it
62-50 -- too much for A&M to overcome with its slow-paced offense.

"We got deflated by a mistake," Blair said. "They didn't have
to earn a couple of those baskets when it went from five to eight
to 10 to 12. They were so easy a couple of sports writers could
have scored."

Charlette Castile led A&M with career highs of 20 points and six
3-pointers. No one else reached double figures for the Aggies, who
missed their first eight shots and 20 of the first 23.

Morenike Atunrase, the Aggies' leading scorer with a 10.7
average, had only six points on 3-for-17 shooting.

A 13-1 run gave Iowa State a 20-7 lead, but the Cyclones'
offense stalled after that and they found themselves fending off
the Aggies the rest of the way. A&M drew to 27-22 on Castile's 3
with 13 seconds left in the half, but Fox hit a 3 from the left
corner with 2 seconds remaining for a 30-22 lead.

"Who hit the 3 right before the half?" Blair asked.

"Fox," a reporter replied.

"Oh yeah," Blair said.
